State Executive# The State Executive is responsible for overseeing the day-to-day management of the Party, subject to State Council direction. It is subordinate to and responsible to State Council.# The State Executive will comprise the State Convenor, State Secretary, Assistant State Secretary, State Treasurer, the convenors of the Victorian Campaign Committee and the Policy Steering Committee established under this Constitution, and seven general members.# The State Convenor, State Secretary, State Treasurer and the convenors of the Victorian Campaign Committee and the Policy Steering Committee will be elected in accordance with the procedures set out for each of them in this Constitution (see sections16. ,54. and60. ).# The general members of the State Executive will be elected annually by and from the members of State Council, in accordance with the relevant bylaws, such that:# three general members are elected for one year terms (except at the20. 15 election only, where five general members will be elected); and# two general members are elected for two year terms. Casual vacancies for general member positions which fall more than one month before the expiry of the term will be filled by State Council from among its members for the remainder of the relevant term.# 5. The State Executive will have all the general powers of State Council, subject to such conditionsas the State Council may determine, other than:1. the power to make, repeal or amend policy; 2. the power to adopt an annual or like budget; 3. the power to appoint members to the Administrative Review Panel and Misconduct Panel; and4. the powers under clauses76. .5,76. .7 and91. . 6. The State Executive will meet as often as required, but must meet at least once every monthwhen the State Council is not meeting, except in December and January. The quorum for ameeting of State Executive will be the next integer greater than half the number of votingmembers of the State Executive for the time being, including the occupants of not less than twoof the Office Bearer positions. For the purpose of determining a quorum, not more than one ofthe Secretary or Assistant Secretary may be counted. 7. State Executive will require its decisions to be ratified by the State Council at the earliestopportunity, provided that the failure or refusal of State Council to ratify any decision by theState Executive will not transfer from the AGV to any member of the Executive any liability foractions taken in good faith, nor will it void any action taken in consequence of any Executivedecision so taken prior to the State Council meeting in which the decision is considered. 8. The State Executive has a responsibility to supervise and co-ordinate the activities of theStanding Committees of State Council and to ensure the integration of the work of thosecommittees, but will not have the power to direct the Standing Committees. The State Executive is responsible for overseeing the day-to-day management of the Party, subject to State Council direction. It is subordinate to and responsible to State Council.# The State Executive will comprise the State Convenor, State Secretary, Assistant State Secretary, State Treasurer, the convenors of the Victorian Campaign Committee and the Policy Steering Committee established under this Constitution, and seven general members.# The State Convenor, State Secretary, State Treasurer and the convenors of the Victorian Campaign Committee and the Policy Steering Committee will be elected in accordance with the procedures set out for each of them in this Constitution (see sections16. ,54. and60. ).# The general members of the State Executive will be elected annually by and from the members of State Council, in accordance with the relevant bylaws, such that:# three general members are elected for one year terms (except at the20. 15 election only, where five general members will be elected); and# two general members are elected for two year terms. Casual vacancies for general member positions which fall more than one month before the expiry of the term will be filled by State Council from among its members for the remainder of the relevant term.#

Notice of Meetings and Elections# Postal and/or electronic notices will be provided to Members, to:# 1. effect postal ballots and the sending of related ballots papers; 2. provide notice of State Conferences; 3. notify relevant AGV Members of any meeting called to establish a Branch; and such notice, as defined and specified in the bylaws, will be given to all Members entitled toattend such AGV meetings. 2. To facilitate maximum participation in decision-making, AGV meetings should be scheduled, asfar as is practicable, so that:1. Branch meetings precede State Council meetings; 2. A State Council meeting should be held no later than 2 weeks prior to a National Councilmeeting; 3. A meeting of each working group should be held no later than 2 weeks before a meeting ofthe body which established the working group. Copy Decision Making in Meetings# Decisions at all meetings of AGVAustralian Greens Victoria constituent groups will be made primarily by consensus, and a serious attempt at all times will be made towards achieving consensus. Sufficient time will be allowed for discussion of different views, including provision for non-decision making meetings.# Except where this Constitution requires a decision to be made by consensus only, if, after a reasonable period of time, disagreement persists and a decision should not be deferred, the question of moving to a vote on a substantive motion will be resolved by a vote. The procedural question to this effect will be deemed to have been carried if it is supported by at least a75. percent majority.# A substantive motion carried by vote, unless provided for elsewhere in the Constitution, requires at least a75. per cent majority of votes cast. Abstentions may be recorded but will not count as a vote, either for or against.# When voting occurs, it will be conducted by a show of hands, except in the case of contested elections which will be determined by a ballot. Voting of all members of the group will be recorded. Voting by proxy will be allowed at meetings of constituent groups if specifically allowed by the bylaws.# A motion regarding a procedural question is carried if a majority of valid votes are in favour of the motion. Abstentions do not count as a vote, either for or against. For the purposes of this clause, a procedural question includes proposals deemed to be procedural questions under Standing Orders issued by the State Council as a bylaw.# Notwithstanding the provisions of clause 48.5, a procedural motion to:# 1. put a substantive motion to a vote; or2. suspend the operation of the Standing Orders; will require at least a75. per cent majority of votes cast. 7. All AGV meetings and processes should ensure maximum participation of all involved,including by using small group discussions, subcommittees or working parties whereappropriate. 8. All meetings of the AGV will be open to all AGV Members and invited members of the generalpublic. At meetings of constituent groups consisting of elected representatives or delegates, thedegree of participation of non-representatives/delegates can be constrained as detailed elsewherein this Constitution as well as at the discretion of the meeting facilitator/convenor. 49 Decision Making through Postal or Electronic Ballots 1. A constituent group meeting may decide to poll relevant AGV Members through a postal orelectronic ballot (to be funded by the constituent group). For the results of the ballot to be valid,a minimum of10. per cent of the AGV members polled must have participated in the ballot. For amotion to succeed it must be approved by at least75. percent of the valid votes cast. 2. Provision will be made available for important or contentious issues for the AGV to be resolvedby postal or electronic ballot of all Members, and will be convened if initiated by10. % ofindividual AGV Members. For the results of the plebiscite to be valid, a minimum of10. per centof AGV Members must have participated in the plebiscite. For a motion to succeed it needs to beapproved by at least75. per cent of the valid votes cast. 3. State Council must decide on how the motions will be put on the ballot paper, as well as howsupporting and opposing arguments will be made available to Members with the ballot paper. 4. When an electronic ballot is held, State Council must make adequate alternate votingarrangements for eligible Members who are not readily able to access the relevant electronicmeans. 5. Postal or electronic votes will be counted by the Returning Officer appointed by the StateCouncil. 6. State Council may make further provision for the manner of conducting electronic or postalballots in a bylaw. Copy Quick Decision Making# Any Party body of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria may establish and (at each year’s AGMAnnual General Meeting) elect members to a Quick Decision Making Group (QDMGQuick Decision Making Group) comprised of members of that Party body, to facilitate the making of urgent decisions. A casual vacancy may be filled from time to time.# The functions and powers of a Quick Decision Making Group (QDMGQuick Decision Making Group) are as follows:# 1. The QDMG will make decisions for the Party body regarding any matter of such urgencythat it must be resolved before the next scheduled meeting of the Party body; 2. Whilst it is the Convenor who is normally required to attempt to contact all QDMGmembers, if necessary, any member of the QDMG can call the meeting. 3. The composition of the Quick Decision Making Group (QDMG) is as follows: 1. The QDMG for the State Executive will comprise the State Convenor, the State Secretary,the State Treasurer and three persons appointed by and from the other members of theState Executive; 2. For all other Party bodies, the QDMG will comprise any two of that Party body’sConvenor, Secretary, and Treasurer (if it has one), and two other persons elected from theother members of the Party body; 3. quorum will be four decision-making members of the State Executive’s QDMG, or threemembers for any other Party body’s QDMG. 4. Procedures for the Quick Decision Making Group (QDMG) include the following: 1. The QDMG will meet only as often as essential; 2. The QDMG may meet face to face or by teleconference, or by electronic communication.In emergencies, the QDMG may simply engage in telephone consultation; 3. In matters relating to particular regions or issues, the QDMG will consult where possiblewith constituent groups or Party Members who may be directly affected by the decision; 4. The QDMG’s decisions will be made by consensus only. 5. The Quick Decision Making Group (QDMG) must keep a written record of any decisions madeand present it to the next meeting of its Party body. 6. Decisions of a Quick Decision Making Group (QDMG) take effect immediately. If a decision ofa QDMG is not ratified by the conclusion of the next quorate meeting of its Party body, thedecision lapses and, to the maximum extent possible, is to be taken to have never been made. Decisions at all meetings of AGVAustralian Greens Victoria constituent groups will be made primarily by consensus, and a serious attempt at all times will be made towards achieving consensus. Sufficient time will be allowed for discussion of different views, including provision for non-decision making meetings.# Except where this Constitution requires a decision to be made by consensus only, if, after a reasonable period of time, disagreement persists and a decision should not be deferred, the question of moving to a vote on a substantive motion will be resolved by a vote. The procedural question to this effect will be deemed to have been carried if it is supported by at least a75. percent majority.# A substantive motion carried by vote, unless provided for elsewhere in the Constitution, requires at least a75. per cent majority of votes cast. Abstentions may be recorded but will not count as a vote, either for or against.# When voting occurs, it will be conducted by a show of hands, except in the case of contested elections which will be determined by a ballot. Voting of all members of the group will be recorded. Voting by proxy will be allowed at meetings of constituent groups if specifically allowed by the bylaws.# A motion regarding a procedural question is carried if a majority of valid votes are in favour of the motion. Abstentions do not count as a vote, either for or against. For the purposes of this clause, a procedural question includes proposals deemed to be procedural questions under Standing Orders issued by the State Council as a bylaw.# Notwithstanding the provisions of clause 48.5, a procedural motion to:#

In this Schedule:# Committee means the Constitutional Votes Committee;# election, including in the term ‘by-election’, means State Council election; and# standard term means a term:# beginning on 1 July of the year of the scheduled election, or on the day the election is declared, whichever is later; and# ending on 30 June two years after the year of the scheduled electionAn election must be held each year beginning with the call for nominations no earlier than 1 February and ending with the declaration of which candidates are elected no later than 31 May.# In this Constitution, continuing State Councillor in the case of a scheduled election—a current State Councillor whose term of office continues beyond 30 June of the year of the election; and in the case of a by-election — a current State Councillor means:# in the case of a scheduled electionAn election must be held each year beginning with the call for nominations no earlier than 1 February and ending with the declaration of which candidates are elected no later than 31 May—a current State Councillor whose term of office continues beyond 30 June of the year of the election; and# in the case of a by-election—a current State Councillor.#

An election must be held each year beginning with the call for nominations no earlier than 1 February and ending with the declaration of which candidates are elected no later than 31 May (scheduled electionAn election must be held each year beginning with the call for nominations no earlier than 1 February and ending with the declaration of which candidates are elected no later than 31 May).# ⌛This clause comes into force on 1 February 2022. The offices open for election at a scheduled election are: in odd years—seven for a standard term;# in even years—eight for a standard term; and# any casual vacancies for a term that continues beyond 30 June of that year that:# exist immediately before the opening of the nomination period; or# will arise on or before 1 July of that year.# # If a scheduled electionAn election must be held each year beginning with the call for nominations no earlier than 1 February and ending with the declaration of which candidates are elected no later than 31 May is terminated or its results are declared void, it must be held again as soon as possible.#

A by-election may be held if there are three or more casual vacancies that are not already open for election at a scheduled electionAn election must be held each year beginning with the call for nominations no earlier than 1 February and ending with the declaration of which candidates are elected no later than 31 May.# The term of office of a State Councillor elected to fill a casual vacancyincludes a vacancy caused by an office not being filled at an election:# begins when they are declared elected or when the vacancy arises, whichever is later; and# ends when the term of office of the vacancy was due to end.#

Each election must be conducted in accordance with the following principles:# equal treatment of candidates;# prevention of improper or unfair influence;# encouragement of the maximum number of nominees;# freedom of debate and truthful communication;# informed voting; and# substantial compliance is sufficient compliance.# The Committee must:# allow a reasonable nomination period;# notify each member in writing of the call for nominations;# notify each member of the date that the roll of eligible voters will be closed;# verify that nominees are eligible to be elected;# reject the candidacy of nominees who are not eligible to be elected;# declare the candidates;# make available to members:# candidate statements;# a statement that reminds members of the need for diversity and sets out the diversity of the continuing State Councillors, so far as it can be ascertained; and# a statement that sets out any disciplinary action a member is suspended for a specified period; or a member is expelled. taken, and convictions recorded, against each candidate in the last 10 years;# run Meet the Candidates events;# run a ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’;# only allow eligible voters to vote;# provide a means for members to raise concerns about the election;# where one or more casual vacancies are open for election, employ a system under which the votes are first counted to determine who is elected, and are then successively recounted to determine which of the elected candidates are elected to which offices, from the longest term to the shortest;# employ a system under which candidates are eliminated from the count and their preferences distributed if, but for their elimination, they would have been elected and that would have resulted in more than three State Councillors being members of the same branch;# declare which candidates are elected to which offices; and# make the results of the ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’ available to members.# The resources of the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) and those at the disposal of a member who holds public officeincludes a member elected or appointed to a public office where the term of that office is yet to begin must not be used to support one candidate against another.#

Before each election, the Committee must make, and make available to members, rules for that election (election rules) that provide for the practical implementation of the principles in item 4(1), the requirements in item ​4(2) and the rule in item 4(3).# Before doing that, the Committee must:# make a draft of the election rules available to members; and# allow members a reasonable opportunity to comment on them.# The election rules may provide that:# certain modes of campaigning are prohibited;# candidates must be assisted by the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) to contact each member; and# election deliberation sessions must be conducted in a certain way.# The Committee may:# make rulings about whether the election rules have been breached;# require a candidate who has breached the election rules to remedy that breach; and# cancel the candidacy of a candidate who seriously breaches the election rules or a ruling of the Committee.#

In this Constitution, election deliberation sessiona discussion of: the issues facing the Party and how they should be addressed; the strengths and weaknesses of the current State Council; the merits of the candidates in addressing those. means a discussion of:# the issues facing the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) and how they should be addressed;# the strengths and weaknesses of the current State Council; and# the merits of the candidates in addressing those.# For each election, before the roll of eligible voters is closed:# each branch must hold at least one election deliberation session; and# the Committee must hold at least five election deliberation sessions.# Each candidate may only attend one deliberation session but must not participate in the discussion.# The failure of a branch to hold an election deliberation session does not, alone, invalidate an election.#

A State Council meeting may be convened: by any five State Councillors; or# in accordance with any procedure made under item 7.#
State Council must give members as much notice of its meetings as it can.
The quorum for a State Council meeting is a majority of current State Councillors, but not fewer than five.

A State Council meeting must decide its own agenda.# The types of proposal that may be put to a State Council meeting are:# a procedural proposala proposal about the proceedings of the meeting at which it is put;# a reconsideration proposala proposal that a resolution of State Council or a senior party body be rescinded; and# a substantive proposalany proposal that is not a procedural or reconsideration proposal.# A proposal that is put to a vote is passed if it meets the following requirements:# Type Requirements Procedural proposal A majority of State Councillors in attendance (except by proxy) who vote on the proposal vote in favour Reconsideration proposal A majority of current State Councillors vote in favour Substantive proposal At least two thirds of State Councillors in attendance who vote on the proposal, and a majority of current State Councillors, vote in favour

A State Councillor may appoint another State Councillor as their proxy to attend, speak and vote on their behalf at State Council meetings.# The appointment of a proxy must be made, and may be terminated before or during its effective period, by written notice given to State Council.# Each State Councillor, in each financial yearThe financial year of the Party is the year ending on 30 June., may appoint:# one proxy for a specified period of up to five weeks; or# two proxies, who may be different State Councillors, for two specified, non‑overlapping periods of up to five weeks in total.# A State Councillor may only be the proxy of one other State Councillor at a time.# A purported appointment of a proxy in breach of sub-item (3) or (4) is invalid.# A proxy must not be directed how to vote.#

Members who hold public officean elected office in a council or parliament at each of the federal, state and local levels of government may appoint a member to attend and speak on their behalf at each State Council meeting.# The party body established for members who are First Nations people may appoint two of its members to attend and speak on its behalf at each State Council meeting.# State Council may, by a procedural proposala proposal about the proceedings of the meeting at which it is put, require that members in attendance at a State Council meeting keep the contents of all or any part of that meeting confidential from other members.# State Council must not limit the entitlement of a State Councillor, or a member appointed under sub‑item (1) or (2), to attend a State Council meeting.#
State Council may, by a substantive proposalany proposal that is not a procedural or reconsideration proposal, make additional meeting procedures that are consistent with these procedures.

In this Schedule: New State Council means State Council under this Constitution;# Old Constitution means the Constitution of the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) immediately before this Constitution comes into force;# Old State Council means State Council under the Old Constitution; and# transition date means 1 January 2023.#

Subject to the rest of this Schedule:# the provisions of the Old Constitution, except for each provision relating to the name of the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1), remain in force until the transition date;# clause 40(1) and Schedules 7 (items 4 and 5 only), 8 and 9 of this Constitution come into force immediately;# the following provisions of this Constitution come into force on 1 February 2022:# clause 4;# clauses 35 and 36 as they apply to the New State Council;# Parts 3 (apart from clause 21(2)) and 4 ; and# Schedules 4, 5 and 6 (apart from item 2(2));# clauses 35 and 36 come into force completely on the transition date; and# the remaining provisions of this Constitution come into force on the transition date.# The term of office of each party office (other than of branch office bearers) under the Old Constitution that would otherwise have ended after 1 July 2022 ends on the transition date.# The term of office of each branch office bearer under the Old Constitution ends on the transition date.# The following clause is added to the provisions of the Old Constitution after clause 95.6 and remains in force until the transition date: ‘95.6A The Misconduct Panel may instead appoint two of its members to hold the office of Convenor, in which case all references to Convenor must be construed to mean either of the Co-Convenors who each individually have all of the powers and responsibilities of the Convenor.’# For the purposes of Schedule 7, item 4(3)(a), any office held under the Old Constitution does not count as holding office as a State Councillor under this Constitution.# This Schedule is repealed on the day after the transition date.#

The first members of the Constitutional Votes Committee are:# the State Returning Officer under the Old Constitution as at 1 February 2022, or both State Returning Officers if that position is shared; and# other eligible members appointed so that the Committee has three members.# The Old State Council must make appointments under sub-item (1)(b) by 1 February 2022.# Any vacancy on the Constitutional Votes Committee must be filled:# before the New State Council is elected—by the Old State Council; and# after the New State Council is elected—under this Constitution.# The offices open for election at the scheduled electionAn election must be held each year beginning with the call for nominations no earlier than 1 February and ending with the declaration of which candidates are elected no later than 31 May held in 2022 are:# eight for a term beginning 1 July 2022 and ending 30 June 2024; and# seven for a term beginning 1 July 2022 and ending 30 June 2023.# Each member is eligible to vote in the scheduled electionAn election must be held each year beginning with the call for nominations no earlier than 1 February and ending with the declaration of which candidates are elected no later than 31 May held in 2022.# The Constitutional Votes Committee must employ a system under which the votes are first counted to determine who is elected, and are then recounted to determine which of the elected candidates are elected to the offices under sub‑item (4)(a).# Any member elected as a State Councillor to the New State Council ceases to hold all party offices under the Old Constitution except Convenor of the Victorian Campaign Committee, State Treasurer and as a branch office bearer.# Vacancies caused by the operation of sub-item (7) may be filled by any procedure decided by the Old State Council.#

Decisions made by the New State Council before the transition date take effect on the transition date.# By the transition date, the New State Council must establish party bodies and provide arrangements that functionally reproduce the party bodies and arrangements in the Old Constitution, and in bylaws made under the Old Constitution, in respect of the following matters: probity, preselection, election campaigning, urgent withdrawal of party endorsement of a candidate for public officean elected office in a council or parliament, misconduct and tithing.#

On the transition date, the following matters carry over:# Old Constitution New Constitution Party policy not made by a branch State policy Party policy made by a branch Local policy Branch Branch Branch boundaries Branch area Working group established by State Council Working group established by State Council with the same terms of reference On the transition date, with the force of a decision of the New State Council, each State Councillor on the New State Council becomes entitled to an annual honorarium of one fifteenth of the total of annual honoraria to which members were entitled under the Old Constitution immediately before the transition date.#

The name of the working group is BlakGreens Victoria (BGV).# These terms of reference for the working group are written with proud acknowledgment of the 38 living First Nations in the colonial state of Victoria. We pay respect to our ancestors and warriors of the frontier wars, our elders and descendants of all First Nations in Victoria. We stand in solidarity for justice and empowerment for our First People. The sovereignty of this land was never ceded. This was, is and always will be First Nations Land.#

BGV is a working group of the Australian Greens Victoria (AGVAustralian Greens Victoria) with the purposes of:# Increasing membership in the Australian Greens Victoria of people from First People backgrounds;# Supporting members with First People backgrounds to participate in Australian Greens at all levels, from local, regional to national membership participation; and# Serving as a forum for expert advice and consultation within the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria on First Nations affairs and policies.#

BGV will work to provide an authoritative voice within the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria for members with First People backgrounds including, but not limited to:# Advocating for First Nations representations within the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria and in local councils or parliaments of Australia;# Advocating for training of members with First People backgrounds to enable them to participate in AGVAustralian Greens Victoria party processes;# Informing the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria party bodies of First Nations affairs, including on campaigning and policies.# In congruence with the Charter of the Greens, BGV shall work to communicate, liaise and advocate for First People communities in Victoria, when requested by these communities, elders or delegates, on issues significantly impacting or of significant importance to these communities.#

BGV shall comprise AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members who identify themselves with First Nations heritage. 7. AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members of non-First People background are welcome to participate as supporters or co-opted members of BGV, when invited by a BGV member.# Co-opted members are unable to exercise a vote or block a consensus.#

BGV shall consist of a core group of office-bearers that include the following positions, with each role ideally shared by two people of different genders:# Convenor / Co-Convenors; and# Secretary / Co-Secretaries; with# Treasurer / Co-Treasurers (if BGV holds funds).# Members of BGV shall elect office-bearers from their number annually, as agreed by consensus by the working group at an annual general meeting (AGMAnnual General Meeting).# In support of office-bearer roles as per clause 9, BGV may elect at the AGMAnnual General Meeting two sets of office-bearers for each role to rotate in 6 monthly rotations to share the duties of the roles.# BGV members shall nominate their Victorian delegate to the Australian Greens First Nations Committee from their membership.# Should any office-bearer position becomes vacant before an AGMAnnual General Meeting, it shall be filled if possible at the next BGV meeting.#

The Convenor(s) shall be responsible, among other things, to:# convene meetings;# ensure meetings are adequately facilitated; and# be the main contact person for BGV.# The Secretary(ies) shall be responsible, among other things, to:# provide notice of meetings;# prepare and distribute meeting minutes;# prepare and distribute meeting agendas; and# keep a record of all proceedings.# The Treasurer(s) will be responsible for all records of financial decisions and transactions. If there is no Treasurer, the Secretary upkeeps the responsibility of the Treasurer.#

BGV shall meet at least once every 3 months.# The quorum for general meetings is 3 members, one of which must be an office-bearer.# Decisions will be made by consensus.# So far as is practicable and possible, each meeting will set a date, time, and venue or electronic method for the next meeting. Where the date has not been set, or must be changed, the Secretary shall advertise the date, time and venue at least 3 days ahead. However, an urgent meeting may be called with no less than 12 hours notice if 3 members, one of which must be an office-bearer, agree that it is necessary.# Notice of meetings shall be provided to all members in advance of each meeting, and members provided with an agenda for that meeting and unconfirmed minutes for the previous meeting.# The confirmation of previous minutes will be considered at each meeting, and confirmed minutes are to be sent to the State Secretary.#

BGV may establish a Quick Decision Making Group (QDMGQuick Decision Making Group) for instances where urgent decisions need to be made before the next scheduled meeting of BGV.# QDMGQuick Decision Making Group membership shall consist of any two of the office-bearers and two other members.# QDMGQuick Decision Making Group decisions must be made by consensus by a quorum of 3 members.# All QDMGQuick Decision Making Group decisions shall have immediate effect, but be put to the next BGV meeting for ratification.# A written record shall be kept of all QDMGQuick Decision Making Group decisions.#

All records of the working group proceedings shall be kept by the Secretary of BGV, and shared with the State Secretary as soon as practical (ideally within 14 days).# If there is a change of Secretary, all records will be passed on within 14 days.#

documents.t: To establish and build a network of Greens party members of the Northern, Western and Eastern Victoria Upper House regions.

To facilitate and properly resource party building in each of the country Upper House regions;# To foster a supportive environment for the pre-selection of candidates in all country seats in Victoria;# To establish a forum for policy discussion and development with regard to interests, perspectives and issues relevant to people living in country Victoria;# To seek representation of those interests, perspectives and issues in the Greens party platform;# To establish a public presence in rural areas and regional centres that will allow country Victorians to engage with the Greens;# To establish a coordinated media and public presence in country Victoria consistent with A.G.V. media guidelines;# To set up I.T. infrastructure and support (website portal, bulletin boards, e lists etc) that facilitates networking across the rural Upper House regions, recognizing the connectivity constraints of country Victoria;# To resource continuous campaigning in each of the rural Upper House regions;# To provide a conduit between country Victorians and Green MPs.#
The Network will be underpinned by the values evident in the Victorian Greens constitution, and meeting protocol.

The Country Greens Network is a loose network of all AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members residing in the rural Upper House regions with an Executive Committee comprising: A representative from each branch in the rural Upper House regions elected by that branch, if the branch chooses to elect a representative;# The representative to the Australian Greens Country Greens Working Group elected by the Committee from amongst all AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members residing in the rural Upper House regions; and# A convenor, an IT officer, and a Secretary elected by the Committee from its membership, or external. Executive group meets a minimum of quarterly (e.g. by email, teleconferencing or other means open to remote communities).#

The office bearers are: Convenor, whose duties include:# Convening meetings# Ensuring the network sticks to these terms of reference# Presenting an annual report to the network conference# Providing a written annual report to State Conference, received by the State Secretary no less than 7 days prior to the Annual State Conference meeting on:# current membership;# meeting activity;# progress on areas that are within the aims; and# any reports from the representative to the Australian Greens Country Greens Working Group.# Providing a written report to State Council immediately following a general election on any campaigning undertaken.# I.T. Officer, whose duties include# Compiling a contact list for the network# Creating and maintaining the network portal website# Keeping a current email list# Secretary, whose duties will include:# Arranging for minutes to be taken and the copy passed to State Secretary# Work with IT officer to update website content# Develop the use of social media for CGNCountry Greens Network# Membership development with emphasis on connecting with CGNCountry Greens Network members where there are no branches.#

Dates of all meetings will be determined by the current convenor in conjunction with ExecState Executive committee;# The State Secretary will be advised of ALL meetings to be held;# The minimum required number of meetings annually shall be 4;# Notice of any meeting shall be advertised on the network email site;# Attendance is open to all financial members of the Australian Greens, Victoria and attendees have speaking rights;# The minimum reporting requirements are (a) Name of Network (b) Date of meeting (c) Persons in attendance (d) Decisions made# Decision making – see Decision Making at Working Group Meetings#

Open to interested financial party members residing within the Northern, Western or Eastern Victoria Upper House region boundaries;# The State Convenor is an ex-officio member of this network, and the State Policy coordinator is an ex-officio member for all policy discussions;# The means of communication for the network shall be email and website;# It is incumbent upon membership to inform themselves of meetings and keep abreast of developments;# The email list/site shall contain all those financial members who wish to be on the list;# The content of all emails will be non-confrontational, but constructive#
To be approved by the Country Greens Network executive group responsible to the branches that form the network. No ability to incur debt or unfunded liabilities.
Public comment will be made through elected representatives, or members nominated by the Country Greens Network executive and subsequently appointed by State Council.

A minimum of one annual review will be made by State office bearers to consider the overall functioning and effectiveness of the network. A copy of the current terms of reference must be displayed on the internal AGVAustralian Greens Victoria website. In the event that the it fails to meet its minimum meeting and reporting requirements, or in any instance where it is seen to be breaching party rules, the State Council may choose to dissolve the group.

Decisions shall be made in accordance with Section 48 of the party’s State Constitution, ‘Decision Making in Meetings’ as summarized below: Decisions will be made primarily by consensus and a serious attempt at all times will be made towards achieving consensus. However, if disagreement persists, and a decision cannot be deferred, the question will be resolved by vote. A procedural question to this effect will be deemed to have been carried if it is supported by at least a 75% majority.# Delegates’ abstentions may be recorded but will not count as a vote, either for or against.# Voting by proxy is not allowed.# When voting occurs it will be conducted by a show of hands.# Voting of all members will be recorded.#
State Council is made up of 15 State Councillors.

Drafting Panel commentary Clause 18 sets out the general powers of State Council. State Council must ensure that the party has a party strategy and must establish party bodies and offices to assist it to implement that strategy (clause 18(3)). State Council is responsible for the management of the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1).# State Council may exercise all of the powers of the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) except those of the Constitutional Votes Committee.# In carrying out its responsibilities, State Council must:# ensure that the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) has a party strategy;# establish party offices and party bodies to assist it to implement the strategy;# oversee the implementation of the strategy; and# report regularly to each member about its work and the affairs of the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1).# ❗This power must not be delegated. If a member of the Constitutional Votes Committee is no longer eligible to be appointed to that office, State Council must declare that they are removed from office.# A decision of the Constitutional Votes Committee overrides a decision of State Council to the extent of any inconsistency.# Each State Councillor must:# Drafting Panel commentary Clause 18(6) requires State Councillors to make themselves aware of the requirements of party governance and to prioritise their State Council work over other party responsibilities. become familiar with the Actthe Associations Incorporation Reform Act 2012, this Constitution, the party handbook and the party archive;# conscientiously participate in the work of State Council; and# give priority to their responsibilities as a State Councillor over any other party responsibilities.#

Drafting Panel commentary Clause 19 makes clear that State Council can delegate its powers to other bodies; for example, to an election campaign management committee. However, [Schedule 4](/agvrules/proposed-constitution/schedule-04-powers-state-council-must-not-delegate) sets out a range of fundamental decisions that State Council cannot delegate. State Council may delegate its power, including this power to delegate, subject to any condition or limitation.# State Council must not delegate the powers listed in Schedule 4.# If State Council considers that the decisions of a party body it has established should be subject to reconsideration proposals, it must give it the status of senior party bodya party body given that status under clause 19(3).#
The State Council meeting procedure is in Schedule 5.

State Councillors are elected under the procedure in Schedule 6.# ⌛This clause comes into force on 1 January 2023. The eligibility requirements to vote in a State Council election are in Schedule 7.# The eligibility requirements for election as a State Councillor are in Schedule 7.#

Drafting Panel commentary Clause 22 sets out how a State Councillor ceases to hold office. A State Councillor ceases to hold office if:# they resign by giving written notice to State Council;# the date specified in a notice under subclause (2) has arrived;# they are removed from office under subclause (4);# they are removed from office under clause 25(5); or# they are removed from office by special resolutiona special resolution of a general meeting passed in accordance with the Act and clause 39(11).# A State Councillor may resign with effect on a specified date by giving written notice to State Council.# Such notice must not be withdrawn.# ❗This power must not be delegated. State Council may provide, in relation to subsequent State Council meetings only, that State Councillors are removed from office if they fail to attend a specified number of State Council meetings within a specified period.# A State Councillor is not regarded as failing to attend a State Council meeting if:# State Council has given them leave not to attend; or# they have appointed a proxy to attend on their behalf.#

documents.s: Multicultural Working Group Terms Of Reference

documents.t: AGV Australian Greens (Victoria)QDMG Quick Decision Making GroupMWG Multicultural Working GroupCALD Cultural and Linguistically Diverse Copy
The name of the committee is the Multicultural Working Group.#

MWG is a state wide group of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria with the purposes of: a) increasing CALD membership in the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria; b) increasing CALD participation in the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria at all levels; c) increasing support for the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria within CALD communities.#

MWG has general responsibility for working towards strengthening opportunities in the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria for people from diverse cultural backgrounds.# MWG will operate as a forum for consultation within the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria on multicultural issues, including AGVAustralian Greens Victoria multicultural policies.# MWG will work to ensure that CALD communities are given an effective voice within the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria. This work can include, but is not limited to: a) advocating for or assisting in the implementation of CALD sensitive election policies; b) facilitating the establishment of CALD community contacts and relationships; and/or c) advocating for multicultural election campaigns and targeted CALD campaigns.#

MWG will comprise any AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members interested in multicultural and CALD issues.# Members of the MWG shall annually elect office-bearers from their number at an annual general meeting. They shall include a Convenor, a Secretary and a Treasurer# Should any office bearer position become vacant, it shall be filled if possible at the next MWG meeting.# The MWG may elect co-office bearers.# A member of the MWG cannot hold multiple office bearer positions within the MWG.#

The Convenor shall be responsible, among other things, to: a) convene meetings; b) ensure meetings are adequately facilitated; and c) be the main contact person for MWG.# The Secretary shall be responsible, among other things, to: a) provide notice of meetings; b) prepare and distribute meeting minutes; c) prepare and distribute meeting agendas; and# d) keep a record of all proceedings. Copy The Treasurer will be responsible for all records of financial decisions and transactions.# The Treasurer will be a signatory, with the Convenor and Secretary of MWG, for the MWG bank account.# Two out of three office bearers can authorise financial transactions.#

MWG shall meet at least bimonthly.# The quorum for general meetings is 50% of office bearers and four members.# Decisions will be made by consensus.# So far as is practicable and possible, each meeting will set a date, time and venue for the next meeting. Where the date has not been set, or must be changed, the Secretary shall advertise the date, time and venue at least five days ahead. However, an urgent meeting may be called with no less than 12 hours notice if at least four of the members, including one office bearer, agree that it is necessary.# Notice of meetings shall be provided to all members, and an agenda will be distributed in advance of each meeting.# Unconfirmed minutes will be distributed by the Secretary within five days of each meeting to all members and to others who were present.# The confirmation of previous minutes will be considered at each meeting, and copies are to be sent to state office.#

MWG may establish a Quick Decision Making Group for instances where urgent decisions need to be made before the next scheduled meeting of MWG. It shall operate in accordance with the provisions set out in part 50 of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Constitution, the main points of which are as follows: a) QDMGQuick Decision Making Group membership shall consist of any two of the office bearers and one other member; b) the QDMGQuick Decision Making Group quorum shall be three members; c) QDMGQuick Decision Making Group decisions must be made by consensus; d) all QDMGQuick Decision Making Group decisions shall have immediate effect, but be put to the next meeting for ratification; and e) a written record shall be kept of all QDMGQuick Decision Making Group decisions.#

All records of the proceedings of MWG shall be kept by the Secretary.# If there is a change of Secretary, all records will be passed on within 7 days.# MWG will provide State Council - immediately following the conclusion of a general election campaign - with a written report of its campaigning.# MWG will provide Annual State Conference with a written report of its: a) current membership; b) meeting activity; and c) progress on areas that are within the purpose and objectives.#

NAME The name of the group shall be Policy Working Group for Housing and Homelessness, which may be abbreviated to the Housing and Homelessness PWGPolicy Working Group, or simply the H&H PWGPolicy Working Group (PWGPolicy Working Group).# PURPOSE AND ROLES It is the purpose of the PWGPolicy Working Group, in co-operation with the Policy Committee and as per the State Council approved policy processes, to: a) develop and review policy in the area of Housing and Homelessness policies and issues, and all aspects of these policy areas, during the four-yearly substantive policy review; b) monitor developments in its policy area(s), and recommend further variation to policy as necessary; c) provide support to elected representatives and other spokespersons of the Greens, at their request; d) provide interpretation advice to the Policy Committee on any question relating to the policy area(s); e) act as a forum for members of the party to discuss issues in all aspects of the policy area with the view of engaging members in the policy review process, engaging and informing members through discussion on interesting aspects of the policy area, and providing support in the policy area(s) for AGVAustralian Greens Victoria campaigns; and f) ensure that internal members-only discussions, including online forums, follow Greens safe-meeting practices.# While the PWGPolicy Working Group does not have the responsibility for developing or implementing political strategy in the policy area(s), or implementing specific initiatives, action plans or campaigns, these will be developed in consultation with the PWGPolicy Working Group where time permits.# LIAISON The PWGPolicy Working Group will consult, as relevant and appropriate, with: a) the Policy Committee; b) constituent groups of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria; c) comparable Greens groups in other states and territories, the federal party, and international Greens groups; and d) other individuals with expertise or interest in the policy area.# The Policy Committee or State Council may request a report or research on any policy matter within its area, at any time during the life of the PWGPolicy Working Group.# TERM OF OPERATION The PWGPolicy Working Group will commence operations when endorsed by the State Council meeting.# The PWGPolicy Working Group is an ongoing working group.# MEMBERSHIP Any financial members of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria shall be eligible to stand for election to the PWGPolicy Working Group.# State Council will elect eight (8) PWGPolicy Working Group members annually from among all the members of the party. In addition, the parliamentary portfolio holder or spokesperson shall be a member of the PWGPolicy Working Group, and a local councillor selected by the local council representatives shall be added to the PWGPolicy Working Group.# Where an extraordinary vacancy exists after an election has been held, PWGPolicy Working Group members may be appointed by approval of the State Council.# Members have an obligation to actively participate in and contribute to the development or review of a policy.# A membership attendance list will be kept and registered with the State Secretary.# Attendance and participation at meetings, as per meeting procedures below, is open to all members of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria.# A PWGPolicy Working Group member will cease to be a member following absence from three consecutive meetings without notice, provided that the Convener may grant special leave of absence from meetings of the PWGPolicy Working Group to any member.# OFFICE BEARERS Members of the PWGPolicy Working Group shall annually elect from among themselves a Convener and Secretary.# Where an extraordinary vacancy exists, an office bearer may by appointed by agreement of the PWGPolicy Working Group.# MEETINGS The PWGPolicy Working Group shall meet at least once per quarter, either in person or remotely.# Notice of meetings will be advertised in advance through the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria e- bulletin, and per email to branch secretaries and members registered with the PWGPolicy Working Group.# A quorum of any meeting of the PWGPolicy Working Group shall be at least half of PWGPolicy Working Group members.# A meeting agenda will be provided to all PWGPolicy Working Group members and other AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members registered with the PWGPolicy Working Group prior to the meeting, and will be confirmed at the beginning of the meeting.# Actions agreed and decisions made at a previous meeting will be taken as ‘not for further discussion’, unless a specific agenda item with a written proposal is forwarded to the Convener prior to the meeting.# Decisions are generally made by consensus of all present at a meeting. However, in the event that consensus cannot be reached, a 75% majority of PWGPolicy Working Group members present can be taken as the decision.# REPORTING AND ACCOUNTABILITY A list of decisions made by the PWGPolicy Working Group will be minuted and distributed to# members of the PWG and to the Policy Committee. Copy The Convener will keep the State Council and Policy Committee informed of progress and activities as appropriate, with an annual written report on the group’s activities.# The Convener must respond to any written correspondence from the Policy Convener or State Secretary.# In the event that the PWGPolicy Working Group fails to meet its minimum meeting and reporting requirements, or in any instance where the PWGPolicy Working Group is seen to be breaching party rules, the State Council may choose to dissolve the group.# The PWGPolicy Working Group shall not make any public statements without the prior approval of the relevant AGVAustralian Greens Victoria spokesperson.# POLICY CONTENT CHANGES Any agreed recommendations for policy changes by the PWGPolicy Working Group are to be presented to the Policy Committee for review and presentation to State Council for ratification. Whether the recommendations have been agreed by consensus or by the standard 75% vote shall be indicated to the Policy Committee.#

AGMAnnual General Meeting - Annual General Meeting AGVAustralian Greens Victoria - Australian Greens Victoria LGBTIQA+ - Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual/Biromantic, Transgender/Trans, Intersex, Queer, Asexual/Aromantic QGVQueer Greens Victoria - Queer Greens Victoria
The name of the group shall be the Queer Greens Victoria (QGVQueer Greens Victoria).#

The QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall be open to all members of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria who identify as LGBTIQA+ and support the empowerment, equal opportunities, rights, safety, economic independence and self-determination of all LGBTIQA+ people within an intersectional framework.# AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members who do not identify as LGBTIQ may actively participate in the QGVQueer Greens Victoria but may not vote, block consensus or be office bearers.# The QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall annually elect a Convenor, Secretary, and Treasurer at an AGMAnnual General Meeting. The working group may elect co-office bearers for any of these positions.# In the event that the group elects to have co-office bearers, it is desirable that at least one of these not identify as a cisgender male. If nominating for a shared position, the nominees must nominate as a joint ticket.# The annual election of office bearers may be done by either of: (a)attendance election by either of consensus or paper ballot at a QGVQueer Greens Victoria AGMAnnual General Meeting; or (b)postal or electronic ballot of all eligible and registered QGVQueer Greens Victoria members.# QGVQueer Greens Victoria may elect additional office bearers when required.# Casual Vacancy Elections of Office Bearers may be done by either of: (a)attendance election by either of consensus or ballot; or (b)postal or electronic ballot of all eligible and registered QGVQueer Greens Victoria members.#

The QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall serve as a forum for the engagement of LGBTIQA+ people and their allies in the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria and support the empowerment, equal opportunities, rights, safety, economic independence and self- determination of all LGBTIQA+ within an intersectional framework.#

The QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall promote and facilitate the involvement of LGBTIQA+ people within an intersectional framework in the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria and local branches.# The QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall encourage and grow membership of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria within LGBTIQA+ communities and support LGBTIQA+ members to take roles of responsibility within the party.# The QGVQueer Greens Victoria may advocate in the interests of LGBTIQA+ Victorians within the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria and across the broader community, and generate awareness of the issues facing LGBTIQA+ people and their families in Victoria and the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria.# The QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall ensure that the human rights of LGBTIQA+ people and families are protected and advanced within AGVAustralian Greens Victoria policies.# The QGVQueer Greens Victoria may contribute to AGVAustralian Greens Victoria policy development within the scope of any policy development process agreed to by the State Council.# The QGVQueer Greens Victoria may provide information on issues facing LGBTIQA+ people to elected AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members and support the delivery and implementation of policies relevant to LGBTIQA+ people.# The QGVQueer Greens Victoria may assist with or coordinate electoral or other campaigns that are consistent with AGVAustralian Greens Victoria policy or decisions of the Victorian Campaign Committee.# The QGVQueer Greens Victoria may fundraise for and support the election of LGBTIQA+ candidates at elections, consistent with decisions of the Victorian Campaign Committee.#

The QGVQueer Greens Victoria has no authority to incur debts or secure loans on behalf of the party.# The QGVQueer Greens Victoria may make arrangements with the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria State Treasurer to open and operate a bank account.# The QGVQueer Greens Victoria will only expend funds provided by the party where this is an accordance with an agreed budget or proposal agreed to at a QGVQueer Greens Victoria meeting.# The QGVQueer Greens Victoria Treasurer in consultation with the QGVQueer Greens Victoria Convenor will be responsible for approving expenditure in the budget, although any QGVQueer Greens Victoria member may request funding for activities.#

QGVQueer Greens Victoria may operate an internal AGVAustralian Greens Victoria email list.# The QGVQueer Greens Victoria working group shall meet at least four times a year, either in person or via electronic means.# Valid meetings of the QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall be those advertised to the group’s members up to two weeks prior to the meeting date with a quorum of six QGVQueer Greens Victoria members, but the quorum must include at least one QGVQueer Greens Victoria Office Bearer, unless all Office Bearer positions are vacant.# The QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall not make decisions on behalf of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria, except when delegated by State Council to do so.# Any decisions made by meetings of the QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall be minuted and sent to the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Secretary and QGVQueer Greens Victoria members within ten days of the meeting.# QGVQueer Greens Victoria members are expected to abide by social media guidelines as outlined on the relevant platform and guided by AGVAustralian Greens Victoria bylaws around the use of social media.#

The QGVQueer Greens Victoria working group will establish a Quick Decision Making Group (QDMGQuick Decision Making Group) of QGVQueer Greens Victoria members for instances where urgent decisions need to be made before the next scheduled meeting of QGVQueer Greens Victoria. It shall operate in accordance with the provisions set out in clause 50 of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Constitution.#
The QGVQueer Greens Victoria is an ongoing Working Group.#

The QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall provide a written report to each AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Annual State Conference on: (a)current membership; (b)meeting activity; and (c) progress on any areas that are within the purpose and roles.# The QGVQueer Greens Victoria Convenor/s must respond to any written correspondence from the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Convenor and/or Secretary.# The QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall provide a written report to State Council immediately following a general election on any campaigning undertaken.#
The name of the group shall be the Victorian Greens Women’s Network (VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network).#

The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall be open to all members of the Australian Greens (Victoria) (AGVAustralian Greens Victoria) who identify as women. AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members who do not identify as women are permitted to attend VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network meetings, conferences, and events as allies and observers (at the discretion of the office bearers), but may not vote, block consensus or be office bearers.# The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall annually elect a Convenor, Secretary, a Representative to the Australian Greens Women’s Working Group and a Treasurer. Office Bearers will be elected by members present at the Annual General Meeting or, failing consensus being reached, they will be elected by secret ballot of all members present at the Annual General Meeting. When necessary, a Returning Officer will be elected to supervise the conduct of ballots. The group may elect co-office bearers for any of these positions.# The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network may elect additional office bearers when required.# An office bearer may be removed by consensus or a two-thirds majority vote by the members of the VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network.#

The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall serve as a network, forum and social space for members of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria, Greens voters and those who are aligned with Greens issues who are committed to women’s empowerment and gender equality.# The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network will promote and advocate for solutions to address structural issues that impede women, especially marginalised women, from participating fully in electoral politics and free and fair debate within party structures.# The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network will highlight and advocate for gender equality and women’s rights in accordance with AGVAustralian Greens Victoria policy and within an intersectional and feminist framework, promoting respect for women and their equal participation in social, working and economic life.# The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network will support the election of women candidates into leadership and elected representative positions at all three levels of government, and to internal AGVAustralian Greens Victoria leadership roles. In particular, the VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network will support the election of people who have experienced intersectional discrimination.#

The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall work to achieve equal representation of women in elected positions, internally and externally. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network will advocate for systemic reform through measures such as affirmative action in accordance with the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria constitution and best practice.# The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network will function as a network to connect people working towards women's empowerment and gender equality through forums, meetings, training and social events.# The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network will advocate for a gender lens on all AGVAustralian Greens Victoria policies and practices to support and underpin social and economic equality for women.# The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network will support the preselection and election of female candidates for all three levels of government through mentoring, training, information sessions and support, opportunities to volunteer for women candidates, and the# opportunity to meet and connect with elected officials. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network will liaise with the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria state representative on women’s issues where possible to advance the work of the VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network in parliament and the public.# The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall work to raise awareness within and outside the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria of the role of intersectionality in the oppression of women, and to actively redress the impacts of multiple oppressions by supporting women who have experienced intersectional discrimination to take on leadership roles, including as candidates, office bearers, council members and other representatives.#

The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network has no authority to incur debts or secure loans on behalf of the party.# The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network may make arrangements with the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Treasurer to open and operate a bank account.# The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network may only expend funds in accordance with an agreed budget.# The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network Treasurer in consultation with the VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network Convenor will be responsible for approving expenditure in the budget, although any VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network member may request funding from the VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network office bearers.# The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network Treasurer in consultation with the VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network Convenor is responsible for acquittal in coordination with the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Treasurer.#

VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network meetings will be conducted in accordance with AGVAustralian Greens Victoria meeting procedures.# The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network may operate an internal AGVAustralian Greens Victoria email list.# The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall meet at least six times per year, either in person or via electronic means.# Valid meetings of the VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall be those advertised to the group’s members at least 7 days in advance and attended by at least five VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network members including at least one office bearer of the VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network network.# The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall not make decisions on behalf of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria, except when delegated by State Council to do so.# The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network members and participants at meetings and events shall be bound by the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Membership Code of Conduct.# Any decisions made by meetings of the VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall be minuted and sent to the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Secretary within ten days of the meeting.# VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network members are expected to abide by social media guidelines as outlined on the relevant platforms.#

VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network may establish a Quick Decision Making Group (QDMGQuick Decision Making Group) for instances where urgent decisions need to be made before the next scheduled meeting of VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network. It shall operate in accordance with the provisions set out in part 50 of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Constitution, the main points of which are as follows:# a)QDMG membership shall consist of any two of the office bearers and two other members;b)the QDMG quorum shall be three members;c)QDMG decisions must be made by consensus;d)all QDMG decisions shall have immediate effect, but be put to the next meeting for ratification; ande)a written record shall be kept of all QDMG decisions.
