The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network is an ongoing Working Group.#

The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall provide a written report to each AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Annual State Conference on:# a)current membership; b)meeting activity; c)progress on areas that are within the purpose and roles; and d)any reports from the Representative to the Australian Greens Women’s Working Group. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network Convenor/s must respond to any written correspondence from the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Convenor and/or Secretary.# The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall provide a written report to State Council immediately following a general election on any campaigning undertaken.#
The name of the working group shall be the J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC).#

The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall promote the alignment of progressive Jewish community with that of the Australian Greens, and support opportunities for the membership and participation of Jewish people within the Greens.#

Membership of the J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall be open to all financial paid up Jewish members of the Australian Greens Victoria and to non-Jewish members of the party who support this group.# 3.1. The J-Greens (VIC) shall encourage attendance and participation by Greens aligned Jewish citizens whoshall hold non-voting member status, subject to the consensus decision of the Members of the Meeting to whichthey are attending. 3.2. Non-voting member shall be excluded from any matters which are subject to party confidentiality. 3.3. Member status may be revoked and such revocation may take place by special majority of wither existingmembers or, when there is urgency, the QDMG will make a immediate determination which subsequently will beconfirmed in the following meeting. Copy The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall annually elect a Convenor, Treasurer and Secretary at an Annual General Meeting.# The group may elect co-office bearers. In the event that the group elects to have co-office bearers, it is desirable that at least one of these identify as a woman.# The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) may elect additional office bearers when required.# Should any office bearer position become vacant, it shall be filled by a vote of all members present at the next J- Greens (VIC) meeting.# The Secretary will maintain a list of current members of J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) for the purposes of advertising and conducting meetings, and conducting ballots to elect office-bearers.# A member of the J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) cannot hold multiple office bearer positions within the J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC).#

The Convenor or Co-Convenors shall be responsible, among other things, to: a)convene meetings; b)ensure meetings are adequately facilitated; and c)be the main contact person for J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC).# The Secretary or Co-Secretaries shall be responsible, among other things, to: a)provide notice of meetings; b)prepare and distribute meeting minutes;# c)prepare and distribute meeting agendas; andd)keep a record of all proceedings. Copy The Treasurer will be responsible for all records of financial decisions and transactions. The Treasurer will be responsible for ensuring the J-GreensJewish Greens adheres to all relevant AGVAustralian Greens Victoria By-laws regarding financial governance, including those relating to ethical review of donations.# The Treasurer will be a signatory, with the Convenor or Co-Convenors and Secretary or Co-Secretaries of J- Greens (VIC), for the J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) bank account.# Two out of three office bearers must authorise financial transactions.# The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall offer access to an reference experts group to give advice on Jewish matters during normal Parliamentary business, during elections, on election strategy and to all elected representatives.# The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) may work with members, branches, working groups and all levels of the Greens to promote effective means of engagement with the Jewish community.# The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) may develop resources, provide training and mentorship to elected representatives and Greens spokespeople about Jewish issues, and the way local Victorian issues can be deeply affected by Israel & Palestinian affairs.# The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall support other groups and bodies within the confederation of Australian Greens to share and develop multicultural awareness.#

The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) has no authority to incur debts or secure loans on behalf of the party.# The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) may make arrangements with the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria State Treasurer to open and operate a bank account.# The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) will only expend funds provided by the party where this is an accordance with a budget that has been ratified by State Council.# The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) Convenor and Treasurer will be responsible for approving expenditure in the budget, although any J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) member may request funding for activities# The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) Convenor and Treasurer are responsible for acquittal in co-ordination with the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Treasurer.#

J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) meetings will be conducted in accordance with AGVAustralian Greens Victoria meeting procedures.# The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) may operate an internal AGVAustralian Greens Victoria email list.# The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall meet at least once per quarter, either in person or by phone or videoconference.# Valid meetings of the J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall be those advertised to the group’s membership in advance and attended by at least five J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) members, including at least one convenor.# The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall not make decisions on behalf of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria, except when delegated by State Council to do so.# The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) members and its office bearers shall be bound by the Membership Code of Conduct.# Any decisions made by meetings of the J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall be minuted and sent to the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Secretary within ten days of the meeting.# Decisions will be made by a serious at consensus at all times (as described part 48. of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Constitution).# So far as is practicable and possible, each meeting will set a date, time and venue for the next meeting. Where the date has not been set, or must be changed, the Secretary shall advertise the date, time and venue at least five days ahead. However, an urgent meeting may be called with no less than 12. hours notice if at least four of the members, including one office bearer, agree that it is necessary.# Notice of meetings shall be provided to all members, and an agenda will be distributed in advance of each meeting.# Unconfirmed minutes will be distributed by the Secretary within five days of each meeting to all members and to others who were present.# The confirmation of previous minutes will be considered at each meeting, and copies are to be sent to state office# The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall manage a secure online forum (such as Facebook) for members and observers that has the following purpose: To provide an avenue for progressing matters related to Jewish Greens Victoria’s mission to “​ promote the alignmentof progressive Jewish community with that of the Australian Greens, and support opportunities for the membershipand participation of Jewish people within the Greens ​.” Posts, discussions, and comments should stick to matters relevant to this mission. The convenor holds responsibility of removing any items which depart or distract from furthering our mission with approval of QDMGQuick Decision Making Group.#

J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) may establish a Quick Decision Making Group (QDMGQuick Decision Making Group) for instances where urgent decisions need to be made before the next scheduled meeting of J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC). It shall operate in accordance with the provisions set out in parts 50-55. of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Constitution, the main points of which are as follows:# QDMGQuick Decision Making Group membership shall consist of any two of the office bearers and two ordinary other member;# the QDMGQuick Decision Making Group quorum shall be three members;# QDMGQuick Decision Making Group decisions must be made by consensus;# all QDMGQuick Decision Making Group decisions shall have immediate effect, but be put to the next meeting for ratification; and# a written record shall be kept of all QDMGQuick Decision Making Group decisions.#

The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) is an ongoing Working Group.# In the event that the J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) fails to meet its minimum meeting and reporting requirements, or in any instance where the J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) is seen to be breaching party rules, the State Council of the Australian Greens Victoria may choose to dissolve the group.#

The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall provide a written report to each AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Annual State Conference on: a)current membership; b)meeting activity; and c)progress on areas that are within the purpose.# The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) Secretary must respond to any written correspondence from the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Convenor and/or Secretary at the next available meeting.#

All records of the proceedings of J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall be kept by the Secretary.# If there is a change of Secretary, all records will be passed on within 7. days.# J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) will provide State Council – immediately following the conclusion of a general election campaign – with a written report of its campaigning.#

In this Schedule: branch delegate has the meaning given in Schedule 2;# Committee means the Constitutional Votes Committee;# issue has the meaning given in Schedule 2;# joint branch proposal has the meaning given in Schedule 2;# meeting means members’ meeting;# permitted proposal has the meaning given in Schedule 2; and# plebiscite means members’ plebiscite.#

The purpose of a meeting is to:# consider the joint branch proposal and the issue; and# reach consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so.# 📅When calculating a period of days under this Constitution, the period from 24 December to 9 January is excluded. If a meeting is called for, State Council must convene one within 14 days.# 📅When calculating a period of days under this Constitution, the period from 24 December to 9 January is excluded. State Council must give each member at least five days’ written notice of a meeting.# The quorum for a meeting is 50 members.# If a quorum is not present within 30 minutes after the set start time of a meeting:# the meeting is cancelled; and# 📅When calculating a period of days under this Constitution, the period from 24 December to 9 January is excluded. in the case of a meeting called for under Schedule 2, item 4—State Council must convene another one within 14 days.# No meeting may be convened later than six weeks after the first quorate meeting.# The types of proposal that may be put to a meeting are:# a procedural proposala proposal about the proceedings of the meeting at which it is put;# a proposal to call for another meeting;# a proposal to end the meeting and not call for another;# a proposal to make a non-binding resolutiona proposal that was passed;# a proposal to initiate a plebiscite on a permitted proposal about the issue; and# a permitted proposal about the issue (members’ meeting substantive proposalany proposal that is not a procedural or reconsideration proposal).# A proposal under sub-item (7)(e) or (f) may only be passed by consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so if at least 67 members are in attendance.# A proposal that is put to a vote is passed if it meets the following requirements:# Type Requirements Procedural proposal A majority of members in attendance who vote on the proposal vote in favour Proposal to call for another meeting Proposal to end the meeting and not call for another A least two thirds of the members in attendance who vote on the proposal vote in favour Proposal to make a non-binding resolution Proposal to initiate a plebiscite At least two thirds of the members in attendance who vote on the proposal, and at least 67 members, vote in favour Members’ meeting substantive proposal At least 75% of the members in attendance who vote on the proposal, and at least 75 members, vote in favour If a proposal under sub-item (7)(e) or (f) is passed:# the meeting is ended; and# any other meeting called for is cancelled.# If State Council passes the joint branch proposal:# any meeting convened for the purpose of considering it is cancelled; and# State Council must give each member written notice accordingly.# State Council must keep minutes of each meeting and make them available to members.#

📅When calculating a period of days under this Constitution, the period from 24 December to 9 January is excluded. If a plebiscite is initiated on a proposal different from the joint branch proposal, the three branch delegates may, within seven days, by unanimous agreement, decide that the joint branch proposal must also be included (***double plebiscite***).# In the case of a double plebiscite, the Committee must decide whether:# the two proposals are independent of each other; or# one proposal is an alternative (alternative proposal) to the other (primary proposal).# A plebiscite must be conducted in accordance with the following principles:# freedom of debate and truthful communication;# informed voting; and# substantial compliance is sufficient compliance.# If a plebiscite is initiated, the Committee must:# give each member a document that sets out:# the issue and the proposal(s);# the financial implications (if any) of the proposal(s) being passed;# arguments provided by members in favour of the proposal(s);# arguments provided by members against the proposal(s); and# State Council’s position (if any) regarding the proposal(s); and# make reasonable efforts to see that each branch arranges for the proposal(s) to be properly considered and voted on.# Arguments under sub-item (4)(a) must not be attributed to an author.# 📅When calculating a period of days under this Constitution, the period from 24 December to 9 January is excluded. Within 60 days after each member is given the document in sub-item (4)(a): each branch must arrange for its members to consider and vote on the proposal(s) by show of hands and advise the Committee in writing of the results of the vote(s); and# the Committee must convene at least five meetings for members to consider and vote on the proposal(s) by show of hands.# # Each member may vote in a plebiscite only once.# The failure of a branch to arrange for its members to consider and vote on the proposal(s) does not, alone, invalidate a plebiscite.# A proposal is passed if the following criteria are satisfied:# at least 60% of the votes are in favour;# the votes in favour exceed the votes against by at least 3% of the whole membership;# it is not the case that a majority of members at a majority of branch meetings in which votes were cast voted against the proposal; and# where the proposal in question is the alternative proposal in a double plebiscite—the primary proposal was not passed.# The Committee must:# declare whether each proposal (members’ plebiscite proposal) was passed; and# make the results of the vote(s), generally and broken down by branch and other meetings, available to members.# ❗This power must not be delegated. State Council must remove a proposal from a plebiscite if: it is not a permitted proposal about the issue;# it would, if passed, be illegal or involve the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) in illegality; or# it would, if passed, cause the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) to become insolvent or create a substantial risk that the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) will become insolvent.# # The Committee may, after hearing from the branch delegates and State Council, terminate a plebiscite or remove a proposal from a plebiscite if it considers that it has been rendered redundant.#

The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group aims to:# Build spaces and support networks to be a welcoming organisation for people with disabilities;# Help the Greens continue to lead on disability issues; and# Create a mechanism to work with VGVictorian Greens Policy Committee to enrich all policy areas with the knowledge and expertise of members with disabilities about how it may impact people with disabilities.#

Voting members of the VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group shall be members of the Victorian Greens who identify as a person with a disability, have a disability or disabilities or are disabled.# In the case of voting member with decision-making or communicative disability, they may be assisted by supporters or representatives as currently defined in “Equality, Capacity and Disability in Commonwealth Laws.” Supporters or representatives shall be in attendance only when the voting member is present.# A VGVictorian Greens Office Staff Member will be a nonvoting member of VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group.# Two members of the VGVictorian Greens Office Bearers Group will be non-voting members of VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group.# A member of the state Party Room or their representative may be a non-voting member of VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group.# The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group recognises the strength in diversity and intersectionality and welcomes input and participation from people with disabilities who are in other marginalised groups, including but not limited to women, people who identify as LGBTIQ, people from culturally and linguistically diverse backgrounds, and people from regional and rural areas.# Experts, carers and allied health professionals may be invited to actively participate within VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group activities, but non-members of the Victorian Greens may not be a member of VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group or be afforded voting or blocking rights.# Parents of children with a disability are encouraged to join but would not have voting or blocking rights unless the issue under discussion related specifically to children with disabilities such as education or early intervention.#

VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group will elect office bearers on an annual basis or whenever a vacancy arises through accessible voting platforms such as email/online ballots.# The office bearers include a Convenor, Secretary, Delegate to the Australian Greens People with Disabilities Working Group and Technical Assistant. These roles may be shared by up to two people.# All office bearers shall be voting members, where a voting member has nominated for the position. If no voting members nominate for a specific role then it may be opened to non-voting members. Members of Parliament and state office bearers cannot be office bearers of VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group.# The duties of the Convenor comprise:# Ensuring that the appropriate notice of meeting, agenda and motions on notice are provided in good time;# Ensuring that the business of each meeting is properly addressed;# Presenting an Annual Report to the Annual State Conference;# Contacting other available members to convene a quick response to urgent and pressing political matters;# Acknowledging and acting on conflicts of interest as they arise, taking appropriate action, which may include determining where a member should abstain from an activity or decision; and# Performing such other duties as may be required by the VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group from time to time.# The duties of the Secretary comprise:# In conjunction with the Convenor, giving notification of all meetings;# Preparing the agenda of meetings, table correspondence and record the attendance of all persons present;# Ensuring that minutes are kept of all meetings of the WG and that an update of the minutes is distributed within 28 days;# Maintaining and updating a draft agenda for the next meeting and ensure that all parties are kept informed of this agenda;# Co-ordinating the correspondence of the VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group; and# Performing such other duties as the WG may from time to time determine.# The duties of the Delegate to the Australian Greens People with Disabilities Working Group comprise:# Report back to the VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group about meetings of the Australian Greens People with Disabilities Working Group (AGAttorney-General-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group);# Seek guidance from the VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group about decisions being made at AGAttorney-General-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group meetings;# Represent decisions relevant to the AGAttorney-General-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group made by the VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group at meetings; and# Compiling an Annual Report to the Annual State Conference.# The duties of the Technical Assistant/Accessibility Liaison comprise:# Organising the technological side of meetings; and# Ensuring that meetings are accessible, including with interpreters.#

The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group will:# Work with Greens local, state and federal representatives to review, develop and recommend policies across disability and other portfolios to ensure they are accessible and equitable for people with disabilities;# Support and advocate for people with disabilities to take up membership, leadership roles and candidacy for the party;# Be an education resource and reference for people within the party on disability policy and practice; and# Engage with federal and other state Greens disability working groups.# The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group will, in the first instance, collaborate with and take the advice of people with specific disabilities where activities or decisions of the group relate to that specific disability. This includes consultation about which experts are invited to participate in the group.#

The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group has no authority to incur debts or secure loans on behalf of the party.# The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group will only expend funds provided by the party where this is an accordance with a budget that has been ratified by State Council.# The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group Convenor will be responsible for approving expenditure in the budget, although any member may request funding for activities.# The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group Convenor is responsible for acquittal in coordination with the State Treasurer.# The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group may be allocated a budget by State Council to cover the costs of hiring Auslan interpreters for meetings,# 5.c.

The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group will meet not less than four times per year either in person, via video link up or by any other appropriate method available.# Where possible, meetings will be facilitated by a trained and experienced facilitator.# The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group will develop agreed procedures for the conduct of meetings, and act in accordance with Victorian Greens meeting procedures.# All members of the group must be given a previously agreed time to review draft documents submitted in the name of the group before they are submitted and be given the opportunity to recommend changes to them.#

The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group is an ongoing policy and campaigning Working Group.# In the event that the VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group fails to meet its minimum meeting requirement for the twelve-month period between State Conferences or fails to present a report to State Conference, then a VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group dissolution item will be put on the Annual State Conference agenda.#

The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group will provide a brief written report to the State Council meeting immediately following a general election on any campaigning undertaken, with a more comprehensive report to be tabled at each Annual State conference.# The report to Annual State Conference must detail as a minimum:# Current membership;# Report from the VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group delegate to the Australian Greens People with Disabilities Working Group;# Details of meeting activity; and# Progress on areas that are within the roles of the Working Group as defined in the terms of reference.#
